<paragraph pageId="342" pageNumber="343">Diversity.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="342" pageNumber="343">
Worldwide, with about 2,630 species arrayed in six subtribes: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jeannel" authorityYear="1937" genus="Anillina" lsidName="" pageId="342" pageNumber="343" rank="genus">Anillina</taxonomicName>
(about 375 species), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stephens" authorityYear="1827" genus="Bembidiina" lsidName="" pageId="342" pageNumber="343" rank="genus">Bembidiina</taxonomicName>
(about 1,340 species), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jeannel" authorityYear="1949" genus="Horologionina" lsidName="" pageId="342" pageNumber="343" rank="genus">Horologionina</taxonomicName>
(one species), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Giachino, GuÃ©orguiev &amp; Vailati" authorityYear="2011" genus="Lovriciina" lsidName="" pageId="342" pageNumber="343" rank="genus">Lovriciina</taxonomicName>
(four species), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Motschulsky" authorityYear="1862" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Tachyina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="342" pageNumber="343" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Tachyina</taxonomicName>
(about 790 species), and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Erwin" authorityYear="1994" genus="Xystosomina" lsidName="" pageId="342" pageNumber="343" rank="genus">Xystosomina</taxonomicName>
(about 125 species). The Northern Hemisphere contains roughly 55.5% of the world fauna and North America alone 14.8% (about 390 species).
